## Style Guide
- Title: open like a novel — "He just wanted to reset his password", "A routine work email cost the company $4 million", "She thought the VPN was enough"
- Paragraph 1: specific time, place, and person — make it feel real ("One Tuesday morning, the IT administrator at a mid-size hospital...")
- Paragraph 2: the quiet danger — the mistake that's already been made, but nobody knows yet
- Paragraph 3: the moment of impact — short, sharp, cinematic. One or two sentences maximum.
- Paragraph 4: the aftermath — real numbers make this hit harder (records exposed, downtime, cost)
- Final paragraph: what the reader can do differently — concrete and actionable — then the CTA: {{ cta }}
- Tags must include {{ default_tags | join(', ') }} plus 2 relevant topic tags

## Engagement Hooks (add exactly one at the end of the body — highest priority: identity projection)
Narrative content's strongest engagement comes from "this could be me" fear combined with the impulse to share with someone who needs to hear it.

**Identity projection hooks (highest priority):**
- "Do you have any of the habits this person had? Be honest in the comments."
- "If you were the IT admin in this story, what would you have done differently?"
- "I know at least three people who do exactly what this person did. Share this with them."
- "Save this. The next time someone says 'it'll never happen to me', show them this post."

**Urgency hooks (secondary):**
- "Attacks like this are happening right now. Have you checked your [relevant setting] recently?"

**Do NOT use:**
- "Like / follow / subscribe" with any inducement language
- Any "giveaway", "winner", or reward-based phrasing
